                        </td>
                        <td valign="top" width="629" style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,Sans-serif; font-size: 10pt; background-image: url('../html/images/color-tan.jpg'); padding: 4px;" id="Cell108">
                            <p style="text-align: center;"><img id="Picture726" height="80" width="154" src="../assets/images/kichijouten-Japanese-spelling.jpg" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="top" border="0" alt="Kichijoten - Japanese pronunciation" title="Kichijoten - Japanese pronunciation"><br><span style="font-size: 14pt;">Kichijōten 吉祥天, Kichijō <a style="font-size: 14pt; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" href="../html/karyoubinga.html">Tennyo</a> 吉祥天女, Kudokuten 功徳天<br>Goddess of Beauty, Fertility, Prosperity, and Merit<br></span><b>Also spelled Kichijoten, Kisshōten, or Kisshoten.</b><span style="font-size: 14pt;"></span></p>
                            <p style="text-align: center;"><b>ORIGIN = HINDU MYTHOLOGY<br>Sanskrit = Śrī-Mahadevi, Mahāśrī, Mahasri, Lakṣmī, Laksmi<br>Chn. = Jíxiáng Tiān; Korean = Gilsang Cheon 길상천<br><br>In the Jimon </b>寺門<b> branch of Tendai </b>天台<b> Buddhism, Kichijōten is equated<br>with <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#myoken">Myōken</a> </b>妙見<b>,&nbsp; the deification of the Northern Pole Star &amp; Big Dipper.</b></p>
                            <p style="text-align: left;">Kichijōten 吉祥天. Wife of <a href="../html/before-buddhism-hindu.html#visnu">Vishnu</a> (Viṣṇu) in <a href="../html/before-buddhism-hindu.html">Hindu myths</a>; wife or sister of <a style="font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" href="../html/bishamonten.shtml">Bishamonten</a> in Buddhist myths. In Japan she is the goddess of fertility, fortune, luck, beauty, and merit; among some Japanese sects she was the central devotional deity, given individual status as an object of Buddhist worship, but since the 15th / 16th century, her imagery and attributes have been largely supplanted by the <a style="font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" href="../html/benzaiten.shtml">Goddess Benzaiten</a>. Even today, the two are commonly confused. Among existing sculpture and artwork, she is sometimes shown wearing a tiara containing an image of the <a style="font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" href="../html/ho-oo-phoenix.shtml">phoenix.</a> (Note: Must still confirm this <a style="font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;" href="../html/ho-oo-phoenix.shtml">phoenix</a> entry.) </p>
